1931 Thursday 1, Jan.

Spent the morning checking unusual atrox in my collection (i.e., SD County, Sonora, N.W. Arizona, New Mexico) Cook having checked the balance.

Also studied rattles and got a good idea of the method of production. For the first time discovered that the rattle is the hardened result of a hardened exudation from the under skin (not a part of the skin as previously supposed) laid down as a granular and laminated material following the corrugations of the skin below. There is much more to be done on this.

In the afternoon listened to the football game and worked on tabular and totalying sheet forms

Jan. Sunday 4, 1931

Made good progress today on the tables and calculations for the Auto-San Diego County papers. All statistics now copied and most if the tables are ready for the printer. All 1930 statistics are already worked up complete.

Find I have too many papers and ideas under way at once--at least 10 all the way from 10% to 50% complete. This is N.G. too much lost motion and skipping about. Have sorted all unfinished MSS and data into separate envelopes and from now on will try to work on one at a time and finish it.

The next on the list will be the auto paper.

Cleaned up various odds and ends in the afternoon.

1931 Saturday 17, Jan.

Returned from San Francisco on the noon train. Spent most of the afternoon in the office catching up on work. Did some preliminary and preparatory work in the Wash-Or oreganus and boas, that is making sheets ready.

Recd from Volk a small L.g. boylii from Oceanside.

Jan. Sunday 18, 1931

Worked over and completed 30 specimens of oreganus and lutosus from Washington and Oregon, USIVM material. Finished this at noon.

In the afternoon worked on Lichanura. I think the desert form is a valid subspecies. Looked at random for scale differences between Trivirgata and roseofusca but found none. Average differences were indicated which might be good in large series, but there are not enough trivirgata available to check this. There are some interesting scale arrangements on the head that can be checked.

Worked on Schmidt PZS carding and completed same including filing.

Worked a little while on the S.D. Co. paper, but too tired to do much.

1931 Friday 23, Jan.

Made some headway with the paper tonight. Made a rough draft of Fig 1.

Recd today from Mrs. Solvey Melling from San Jose, Lower California.
5 amphibians
94 lizards
14 snakes (4 of the snakes recd alive earlier in the year)

This was a rather good collection and in quite fair condition. The best find was 3 T.o. hueyi.

In the evening, finished the pencil work for the distribution of snakes as shown in Fig 1.

1931 Sunday 25, Jan.

Worked today almost exclusively on color variations in zones.

This proved much more difficult than I had anticipated and took until 9P.M. However, it developed well and is now sufficiently elaborated to become a separate and coordinate section of the paper. Did not quite finish it.

Was surprised to find how different the Yaqui Well--Vallecitos worm snakes are from the coast form. Surely a separate subspecies at least. Only thing that worries me is why is Vallecitos the type locality of what is clearly (by Brg's description) the coast form. Can it be that LeCorte got this at another Vallecitos? Must follow this up.

Salvadora also looks like a good possibility. Only break in the sequence is Cook's specimen from Barrett Dam which is light. (Later: This wasn't from Barrett Dam; Barrett Canyon, Imp. Co.).

Notes:

Kelly L.

Exact location of Vallecitos is unclear as there may be more than one (although it was added as a Location).

1931 Saturday 31, Jan.

Today Cook completed all rattlesnakes, including my own and N.H. up to this date. This includes scale counts and rattles. Includes everything in my collection up to 4126.

Took most of the afternoon attending first meeting of the County Hospital advisory board but got a little tabulating done.

Went to a movie in the evening.

Feb. Monday 9, 1931

Cook told me today that he had caught the following yesterday:

1 Boyles king 3 mi. east of Spring Valley DOR M

1 Red Rattler 5 mi. W. of Jamul
Large. Found under a rock.

1 Gopher. Same place. Found under a rock, more or less impedded in soil. Disgorged a mouse. Medium. Mouse evidently eaten within last few days.

Went to Los Angeles in the afternoon. A clear cool day. 130 miles, 56 in county. New Rose Canyon road
first time over the new pavement. Nothing seen.

"Berkeley Square" tonight.

1931 Tuesday 10, Feb.

Returned from Los Angeles this afternoon. Started at 2:30; arrived at 6:15. Raining near Whittier and Fullerton; cool and cloudy the rest of the way. 130 miles total; 56 in the county; 38 in daylight.
1 T.s. infernalis DOR M San Mateo Creek. Grass & marsh on both sides.

For the first time today noted that the three "T.o. elegans" from Laguna Mt are really "T.o. ordinoides" Can this be ok? And the others from Jacumba seem to be atratus.

1931 Thursday 12, Feb.

Went on to Minnewahwa ranch in the evening. 24 miles nothing seen but some crushed toads. It was a rainy day and evening.

On the way back at midnight Hyla regilla was heard at Jamul, Indian Spring, Helix, Spring Valley, and Lemon Grove. Maybe some toads were seen, can't be sure.

1931 Sunday 22, Feb.

The County ms. is finished at last. Spoke to Mrs. Benchley about it yesterday; she made no promises, but said she would take it up with the Board. I will submit it next week.

Cook went over it today and found a number of typographical errors.

Spent the day on the Lichanura paper and made good headway.

In the evening worked on income tax matters.

Xantusia vigilis Field notes by Sherwin F. Wood.
Clear bright sun - cold strong wind. 10 X.v. collected. Taken with comparative ease in one hours time bet. 12 and 1 P.M. in the Mojave Desert 2 mi W of Palmdale, L.A. County. All were found under dead bushes, in the moist debris under roots or under the park, even sometimes in holes made by termites. They were very easy to capture because of the coolness prevalent in their surroundings. Only one was found in the dead trunk of a Joshua tree, the rest were obtained from dead "clump bush" a common shrub of the desert.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/09/2014 09:35 AM
  • Kelly L. 05/27/2012 08:37 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Feb. Monday 23, 1931

Worked all morning on Appendix 3 and checking zonal data. This appendix was a new idea last night.

In the afternoon I practically finished the Lichanura paper.

Went to a movie "Cimarron" in the evening.

Field notes on Uta stansburiana by Sherwin F. Wood. Collected in back of Glendale at Verdugo Woodlands. Warm sun, hazy sky, cool wind. The Utas were found upon rocks or under rocks and like the others were rather difficult to capture. I found the Eumeces (1 spec.) wandering around in the dead leaves.

At this time of year the Utas are found upon the rocks mostly and are sometimes very difficult to capture.

This and the card entries from the two ledgers are the only work unfinished as of this date as far as miscellaneous filing is concerned. Worked on the Oklahoma Sonoras this afternoon.

Mar. Sunday 15, 1931

Spent the morning to good advantage working on the worm snakes. Checked the colors of 47 specimens.

In the afternoon I summarized the results to date, looked up the synonymies and generally surveyed the situation.

Assuming that the absence of the supraocular is at least a specific difference we have at least 3 subspecies i.e. San Diego, Cape and S.D. desert. Arizona is more like San Diego than the others but may be intermediate with Mexico.

Went to a lecture on the Einstein Theory at the Open Forum tonight.

1931 Monday 16, Mar.

Today I saw at the zoo a very large boa from the Narrows. The color contrast was still strong more so than in the coastal specimens although not so much as the juveniles.

Recd today from Benedict a young ruber from Borrego Palm Canyon.

Heard today at the zoo of a young 9 year old who brought in a young rattler in his hands; thought it was harmless.

Worked on worm snake locality records tonight.

Mar. Tuesday 17, 1931

Went out today on a long ride with Savage and NA Eckart of San Francisco. Was in the front seat only part time so trip is not to be counted. Went about 200 miles. Mission Gorge, Santee, Bostonia, Descanso, Julian, The Narrows, Julian (lunch), Morena Dam, Campo, Dulzura, Sweetwater Dam.

A clear warm day. While I could observe the road 12 dead snakes were seen. None alive. Only one could be checked with certainty, a large Pacific rattler at Bingirlle.

Noted Uta stans. and S.o.b. at Morena Dam. (Not new. Don't enter in trip book.)

Notes:

Kelly L.

Second paragraph, last word is Bingirlle? I think it's a location, but not sure of spelling or place. Also, last paragraph, term S.o.b. I think is Sceloporus occidentalis biseriatus, but would like another opinion to be sure.

1931 Sunday 5, Apr.

Today went for a ride with GG & P.M.K.. Started at 10:30 - returned at 4:30. 127 miles. A cloudy day, windy and cool in the higher foothills, rather sultry elsewhere.

Went out via Broadway, Helix, and Highway to White Eagle Corner; returned via Campo, Dulzura and Broadway Ext.

Stopped only at one point; lunched bet. Campo and Clover Flat. Hunted here a short time. Saw horned toad and skellies. Phil. Shot a Uta. Also saw Orcutti. Caught a Rana hopping near a stream in grass but not in water. Also saw skellies at Pine Valley Grade and Orcutti at Indian Spring.

Snakes seen as per opposite page.

Spent the rest of the day, morning and evening working on the County paper.

1931 Saturday 11, Apr.

This morning started for Hoover Dam at 11:18 AM. Weather warm and partly cloudy. Breezy. Clear inland. Went via Highgrove where I exchanged reptiles with Garner. He had nothing unusual. He had three boas which were quite distinctly but not evenly marked. Theses were from Box Springs Canyon. On one the stripes were almost yellow.

Reached Barstow at 6:45. Cool and breezy. Miles 194.0 to Co. line 63.9.

1931 Monday 13, Apr.

A clear moderately warm morning but very windy. Started toward Glendale, Nev at 8:40 AM.
1 Phyllorhynchus 4.7 S of Glendale DOR M
1 P.c. deserticola 3.5 S of Glendale DOR L

Both on high mesa within brush and rocks. Turned around bc condition of the road at 17 mi. beyond Glendale.

Stopped for a short time to hunt at Glendale. Hot and very windy. Saw some lizards, probably callys but couldn't get them. Ate lunch here.

Hunted at several points along here and found lizards scarce and wary. Got 3 Utas 40 mi. from Las Vegas. This was a wash on a mesa.

1 Hypsiglena L DOR ~7mi from Las Vegas. Light brush. Had swallowed a lizard.

Returned at 3:30 Still very windy. Miles 128
Took a run north before supper 14 miles. Nothing seen.

After dark took another run north between 7:30 and 8:30 clear and cool. Nothing seen 30 miles. Total for the day 172.

Apr. Tuesday 14, 1931

Started from Las Vegas for Boulder Dam at 8:50. A clear cool day - warmer in the valleys. Hunted in mesquite hummocks 5 mi from Las Vegas and got a whiptail and Uta. Lizards don't seem to be as common as might be expected.

Drove around Boulder City but saw nothing.

At Vegas Landing saw the skin of a rattler (no head) caught there. Light brown punctated ground and dark brown blotches quite evidently a stephensi. Tail had dark but not black rings. Went down through gorge in a boat.

Drove to Lewis Camp and then in SSP Can to substation camp. Then walked 1/4 mile to ruin above damsite. At the ruin saw Utas, Cally and a large black lizard? Left after lunch at 1:45. 1 Cally 15 mi from Las Vegas. As usual, more lizards were to be seen in the rocks, but were rather disappointing everywhere.

Left for home at 3:35. Miles to Vegas Wash and Boulder and back to Las Vegas 66 miles.

(Continued on page April 7th)

Kelly L.

In paragraph 4, I cannot understand "SSP Can" - probably a canyon name. Any ideas?

May Wednesday 6, 1931

Went to Julian and back today with Peckham and Ruffin to see proposed Julian and Hurlburd grove lines.

A clear day in the back country and moderately warm; high fog at the coast. Started at 10 AM; returned at 5:30. 132 miles. Had car trouble at Pine Hills due to short circuit in battery lead which delayed us about 2 hours.

Itinerary: Broadway ext, Spring Valley, Helix, Grossmont, El Cajon, Ramona, Goose Valley, Ballena, Julian, Pine Hills, Julian, Cuyamaca, Hurburds, Old Viejas grade, Alpine, La Mesa, Broadway. No hunting done except for a few moments while waiting for tow car at Pine Hills.

1931 Saturday 9, May

Today at 1:30 P.M. started for Brawley. A clear warm day. Hot on the desert and quite warm in the back country. Principal purpose of the trip was to secure photos for county paper.

Hunted for a few minutes at Mr. Spring. It was then warm and clear. Lizards seemed quite plentiful. Saw orcutti, mearnsi, skullies, utas, whips and chucks Took a few. Also a collared lizard. Lost a fine chuck in the rocks a/c not able to get it out.

Arrived at Brawley at 7 P.M.
Practically no wind now or later.
1 Rhinocheilus L DOR Alpine Brush.
1 Mitch L DOR Terrinitos Brush
1 Gopher L DOR Live Oak Springs Br-Rocks
1 Horned Toad Alpine DOR.
1 Horned Toad Buckmans(alive)
At 8 P.M. we started north toward the county line. Had a tough and fruitless time, although the weather was ideal. Probably due largely to road under repair and a large fresh embankment along side most of the way.

1 Shovel nose L DOR 27 mi N. of Brawley
1 Gopher L DOR 29 mi. N. of Brawley
(Continued under May 8th 31)

Dips were plentiful at 30.5 Creosote bush association. They are as thick here as in mesquite. They take refuge quickly in ground holes. Seem to like to get on observation posts.

Turned around in the Sand Hills at 48.3

June 2, 1931

Today saw a Lichanura roseofusca gracia belonging to Bogert from Dead man's Point, San Bernardino County.
The stripes are very well marked and and continuous from head to tail. There is some roughness along the edges, but on the whole the variation is within a single scale row; i.e. there is a border row in each stripe the scales of which may be colored or uncolred or part one or the other. Below it is heavily mottled. Many of the border scales are dark edged, that is with a third darker color.
The colors are orange rufons and gull gray (Plate L11).
The oculars are 9-9 and lareals 2/2-2/3

1931 Tuesday 16, June

This morning I left the Maryland Hotel at Pasadena at 8 AM and went to Cal. Tech. Got started arranging my snake exhibit and then went to the Council Meeting of the AAAS presided over by Dr. Boaz and held in Dr. Millikan's office. Then back and finished arranging the exhibit.

Went to lunch with R. Rorn of New York and Geo. Myers. In the afternoon went to the meeting of the Icht. Herp. Society. Showed Slevin's film and also took part in the discussion.

In the evening went to supper with Miss Atsatt, Myers, Stillman, Berry, Bogert and others. Talked until 9 P.M. Also rode down toward Pomona a ways. Myers gave me a small rattler taken by Dorn between Roosevelt Dam and Globe, Ariz.

RR Humphrey of the Desert Laboratory Tucson told me of finding a tiger rattler on the West side of Amoli Peak, Tucson Mts. Also two about 7 P.M. in Sabino Canyon. One in the bush about 2 ft. above ground. One under a rock. Both saw them and rattled. Went sideways and back into a bush.

Page Edit History:

June Wednesday 17, 1931

This morning I went to the Council Meeting, then met Storer and went to a meeting devoted to ecology.

Went to lunch with Storer and Dr. W.H. Burt and spent most of the afternoon in Van Rossen's office.

In the evening went to dinner with Sumner and then to a long discussion on the Biological survey animal control program. Got the following locality records from the specimens upstairs.

Col. Crimmins writes me the lepidiis lately sent from El Paso was found fighting with a C. collaris. The lizard seemed to be winning but when it was pried loose the snake bit it and the lizard died in a few minutes.

July Sunday 19, 1931

Spent most of the day working on the pineal characteristics of rattlers. Fins some differences but difficult to evaluate. The spines show differences in members but it is hard to count them as they grade from full size to very small.

There is certainly a definite difference between Crotalus and Sistrurus.

1931 Monday 20, July

Roy Thompson told me today that Joseph Joffe asst. to the Supt. Yellowstone National Park, Yellowstone Park, Wyo stated that no rattlers were to be found in the park which is all about 7000 ft.
Rattlers seldom occur above 6000 ft. They are to be found on the Montana side, just a few miles out of the park.

July Monday 27, 1931

(August 21st Continued)
The long run down to Kirkland Junction is gradually lightening chaparral much like Viejas grade. South of Kirkland it is getting more barren and rocky with more cactus.

5 mi N. of Yarnell we noted R. pipiens but did not collect it.

Stopped on the hillside (north slope) 1 mi. South of Yarnell to hunt for Xantusias and sure enough we found them. They were under slabs not flakes (For details see Xantusia paper). We got 6 and lost 1. We left here at about 3:45 having worked hard and just about tired ourselves out. Less than a mile from the type locality of Arizonae we came to the top of the grade and sight the desert. The down grade is about 5 mi and then we reach the flat.

At Congress Junction there is a dry grassy plain with scattered mesquite, yucca and cacti. Rather sandy.

One Scute L DOR 3 mi. S. of Congress J. desert at the Maucoipa County border we come to the first tree cactus; (cont July 28th)

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/25/2014 06:05 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

1931 Tuesday 28, July

(Aug 21st continued from July 27)
here the desert becomes rolling and very rocky but with small rocks only.

At Wickenburg we met Messrs. Rohrer and Spivey and talked snakes with them for about 3/4 hour. Spivey says mitchellii is found only in red-rocky hills.

There is a rolling desert around WIckenburg.

8 mi. S. of Wickenburg we stopped at a service station where they had several snakes. They had one pink mitchellii caught atthis point and also a King snake with narrow light stripes about 1/2 way between a boylii and a yumensis.

From Wickenburg in to Phoenix there is all desert of varying textures with mountains in the distance on both sides. It was evidently too hot and too early for snakes as nothing was seen. We reached Phoenix at 7 P.M. and fixed specimens before going to the hotel. All showed the effects of the heat. Miles today 117.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/25/2014 06:09 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Wednesday July 29, 1931

(August 20th continued from July 30th)
from Williams to Presott. Certainly it looks like good snake country from 10 mi. W. of Williams to Prescott except this large Chino Valley. It is easy to see why specimens came from Del Rio and Entro but not the area between. There to be rattlers between Drake and Ash Fork.

Arrived at Prescott at 7:30 P.M.
Miles for the day 217.

Thursday July 30, 1931

(August 20th Continued from July 31)
Oreganus or Confluentus.

The country south of Ash Fork is rolling grass covered hills, large junipers, few scattered rocks. The trees became more plentiful as we go south. The soil is red brown.

At Little Hill Canyon 14 mi. S. of Ash Fork there is an increasing roughness and more trees. 20 miles south of Ash Fork it is still rolling but more arid and rocky. 21 miles south we descend to a large grass covered plain. This is the Chino Valley 12 miles north of Prescott we leave the Chino Valley to enter rolling country which becomes very rocky at 10 mi. N. Sater it is less rocky but much out up by streams.

Today was rather disappointing as we reached good lizard collecting grounds too late. Quite evident that lizards must be collected in the morning. I was interested in noting the character of the country
(Continued July 29th)

Friday July 31, 1931

(Aug 20th Continued from Aug 1)

1 med Olive Brown Conflue DOR
6 mi. E. of Flagstaff. Not of pigmy size. No light line around blotches. Large trees here. Pines.

Stopped at the Dean Eldridge Museum 3 mi. E. of Flagstaff.

He had several stuffed snakes and 2 black Pacifics in pickle. Promised me data on these two later. He also referred to Conflues as sidewinders. He had a number of these but the records were uncertain. He had a large scute from Sidonia (Sedona) south of Flagstaff and a Molossus from same point.

There was a heavy rain most of the way between Flagstaff and Williams but the road was not bad.

1 Vagraus DORS 4 mi. W. of Winslow (forest).
1 Molossus DOR 4 mi e. of Ash Fork Junction but this can't be connected as it had a cord around its neck.

The last ten miles approaching Ash Fork looked like good snake either
(Continued July 30th)

Saturday August 1, 1931

(August 20th Continued)
of Meteor Crater. Plain, short grass and far rocks.

We stopped to hunt for a short time 1 mi. S. of Meteor Crater Junction at noon. It was rather hot - uncomfortable. Red earth, short grass and a few red rock outcrops. Holbrookie and whips are common here.

Stopped at Two-guns at 1 P.M. and got a few lizards along the Canyon Diablo bluffs. Hunting was not good - evidently too hot. The Utas perch on rocks.

1 Small reddish to brown conflue D.O.R. 6 mi. W. of Two guns. Short grass and rocks.

Same thing are mile further west. Also 1 medium Pituophis DOR at this point. Canyon Padre is 4 mi. W. of here. Here the territory changes to junipers (at Canyon Padre) Hunted here for a short time but had no luck.

A Winona the terrain changes again, becoming rolling hills and tree.
(Continued July 31)

Monday August 3, 1931

(Aug 19th Continued)
The temperature was about 80. Small firs, junipers, and sagebrush. Quite dry. The roads were also getting worse. The mesas are very rocky but no lizards were to be seen, except a collared lizard at Kearns Canyon.

We arrived and Mishongrove at about noon; ate lunch and amused ourselves about the village. (For a description of the Dance see elsewhere.)

We got started back at 6:15 but had trouble immediately as the washes were soft with rain and the cars ahead had spoiled the road. We got stuck once and hauled one car out. This must have delayed us a full hour so that we missed a chance to travel in the light.

Then we hit several bumps very hard and broke snubber. Thought we had broken springs but it developed afterward we did not.

We got stuck in the mud once
(Continued on Aug 2nd)

Notes:

Szlyna

Unsure of what they broke on the vehicle, snubler, or if he's trying to say muffler. 5th line up from the bottom of the page.

thenry

It's a snubber. That is what they called the shock absorber used in the cars of that time.

Tuesday August 4, 1931

Cook left on the Hancock yacht for Cedros this morning.

(Aug 18th Continued from Aug 5th)

We found that the rattlers taken in the vicinity of Two Guns (where they are called sidewinders) are not so dark as those from Meteor Crater (those were 4 of the former at Two-Guns) at the latter point they are said to be quite common.

The common lizard east of Flagstaff (the tree and sandstone area) is undoubtedly Sceloporus Conrobunus while around Winslow (the rocky, grass area) is Holbrookia Masculata Approximans.

We got back to Holbrook at 8:40.
Miles for the day 191.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/01/2014 10:11 AM

Wednesday August 5, 1931

Sam Harter and companion left today for the Argus Mts.
----------------------------------------------
(August 18th Cont from Aug 6th)

After Holbrook we went east on US 70 to the Petrified Forest. This country is more rolling and with a heavier grass cover; it ought to be better snake country. At the Forest there are large limestone outcrops. The custodian said snakes were found there but that they were uncommon.

Returning to Holbrook we went east on US 66 as the cut-off from the Petrified Forest through Adamana was washed out. This is also a rolling grassy plain. At one point we passed a rocky gorge due north of Adamana. This must be the place where Hayes got the rattlers last year. We went to Painted Desert Inn but it was too late for the view. Then we went over to Indian Miller's Service Station but found that the boy who told us there was a snake collection was off.

(Continued Aug 4th)

Page Edit History:
  • thenry 04/02/2014 03:17 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Thursday August 6, 1931

(Aug 18th Continued)

There is a sudden change just east of Canyon Diablo. Although the Canyon sides are yellow sandstone, a little beyond the red rock outcrops and from there on into Winslow it is practically all red rock and red earth. This includes Dennison and Moqui but Sunshine was not seen as it is not on the highway.

We had generator trouble on the way in but arrived at 1 P.M. and went into a garage. Here we were delayed 2 hrs.

After leaving Winslow at 3 P.M. we went on into Holbrook. The intervening country is drier and less rocky than west of Winslow and looks like poor snake country. There are a few red rock outcrops; these are large and not scattered. In one place we stopped at one of these outcrops, but no lizards were seen. Across the road there was an irrigating ditch and here Rana pipiens was very common but hard to catch; only one was collected. Not a lizard or snake was seen alive all afternoon.

(Continued Aug 5th)

Sunday August 9, 1931

Miscellaneous records and filing.
------------------------------
(Aug 16th Continued from Aug 10th)

outcrops. Can't tell anything about the lizard fauna as it was too cold and wet today. Saw only one on the mesa and this couldn't be identified. Monday August 10, 1931

Hackberry.

From this point on there are rocky hills. Then 15 mi. W. of Peach Springs begins a long grassy green plain. This gets rough and rocky near Peach Springs and beyond. Here the Junipers are plentiful.

1 Pituophis M DOR 32 mi. W. of Seligman
(= Nelson) Grass and junipers.

(= Crookton)

1 C. oreganus L DOR Crookton grassy - plain.

1 Phrynosoma douglassii 11 miles West of Williams
Arrived at Williams at 6:20 (Pac. T) Quite cool but no rain. Up to Ash Fork the country is still an upland prairie, with green grass and a few junipers. Some rock

Tuesday August 11, 1931

Gloyds arrived from Long Beach this evening.

(August 16th Continued)

Seven miles west of Oatman at Riverview and start to climb. Here are cacti and masses of red brown rock. Then we came to Oatman and Goldrun. We stopped at a point east of the Summit 5 mi. E. of Oatman and got a chuck and whiptail here. A collared lizard was collected 10 mi. E. of Oatman which would be in the Sacramento Valley. After coming down over the hill from Oatman there is a long flat plain (the Sacramento Valley) covered with greasewood. Very few rocks; lizards were not observed here.
Kingman is surrounded by rocky hills. An Indian told us that rattlers were to be found here about but are not common. A big chuck was seen on a rock just E. of Kingman.
There is then a long grassy plain to Hackberry, when it begins to get mountainous and rocky. We got a big chuck alive at
(Continued Aug. 10th)

Saturday August 15, 1931

Today at 1:38 Philip and I started for the Hopi Snake Dance at Mishongnovi, Ariz. Started at 1:38. A clear warm day. 42731

1 L G. Boylii DOR L Lake Hodges Fields
1 C.c. Oreganus DOR M. San Marcos field or ranch
1 L.g. boylii S. DOR Bonsall, Brush
Riverside Co. Line 42797 miles in County 66
C. Wislizenii S DOR Hodge, S.B. Co desert
C. Scutulatus T odd. Found on the road. Evidently just run over at 7:40. Still lively but badly hurt.

Arrived at Needles at short time before midnight 11:50 and put at a hotel. Total miles for the day 366. Very much disappointed in finding nothing while on the long ride across the desert. It was quite warm in the lower areas; comfortable and cool higher up. We had expected to find a number of small snakes alive or DOR.

It was medium warm at San Diego, quite hot at Elsinore. Cooling at San Bernardino. Trip mileage mechanism not working on speedometer, and trouble with the horn. Stopped to see Garner's snakes at Highgrove. He had

(Continued on Aug. 14)

Sunday August 16, 1931

at Needles. Woke up this morning at 7:00 a clear warm day. Started out at 8:50. Got a dip 5 mi. S. of Needles. On the mesa south of Needles only a few dips were seen. Usual rocky desert looks like fine hunting ground. Stopped to hunt in the wash across the river from Topoek. Large mesquites. Although it looks like fine country, nothing was seen.
Saw a Cally DOR at Topoek.

Stopped to hunt in a sandy and rocky mesquite wash 3 mi. NE of Topoek and got a number of lizards and 1 toad here. It was hot with a small breeze. Lost 2 Toads in a deep hole. Watched a cally chase a Uta Stans. They doubled back and forth at high speed like a dog and a rabbit. Don't know if he was caught.

At 11 AM stopped 10 mi. NE of Topoek but caught only a whiptail. This is the rocky area where lizards were so thick several years ago in May.

Chuckwallas were decidedly less common around Oatman and from there on than on the previous trip in May. Only three were taken and not many more were seen. A chuck was taken at Oatman and C. Collaris was observed. We leave the rocky desert
(Cont. August 11th)

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/22/2014 09:31 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Monday August 17, 1931

This morning we left Williams for the Grand Canyon at 8:50 M.T.; a clear cool morning.

At Grand Canyon we met McKee and Bogert. McKee has caught no rattlers this year. He wants to know more about the Confluentus problem and I promised to send him a map (done later). He promised to send me "Grand Canyon Nature Notes".

Bogert had a number of interesting specimens including a molossus in Havasupai Canyon (Western end of Grand Canyon) and a Sonora on one of the main trails. These are botth new records for the canyon.

On the rally over to the Canyon, we start with Transition and end in the same, but the area between which probably corresponds to that around Calla and Anita on the Santa Fe in Sonoran.

Sage brush is to be seen; no trees except junipers. Although the grass is green the soil looks poor and the vegetation sparse. Saw only one lizard on the way a skelly of some kind.

(Continued Aug. 8th)

Notes:

Szlyna

Had a little trouble making out the start of paragraph 4, if he uses the word "rally over to the Canyon" not sure what he means.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/22/2014 09:51 PM

Tuesday August 18, 1931

Started this morning from Flagstaff at 8:30; a clear warm day.

At Winona, the pines have disappeared and the country is much drier. The firs and junipers are shorter. There are skellies to be seen in good numbers on the scattered sandstone.

5 miles east of Canyon Padre we hunted for about 1/2 hour from 10:45 to 11:15. It was clear and moderately warm, with a light breeze. Holbrookia. m.a. was very easy to collect. They run a short distance and then stop. They zig-zag some and don't take readily to holes. Also we collected here a small confluentus. He seemed quite vicious.

A treeless plain with scattered rocks and low grass with small shrubs begins at Canyon Padre.

At Two Guns (Indian Miller's) we bought a small dark Conflue for 1.00. They are called sidewinders here.

1 Pituophis DOR Two Guns. Rocky plain
1 Hypsiglina DOR 3 mi. W. of Dennison
1 Pituophis DOR 3 mi. W. of Dennison (saved)

(Continued on Aug. 6th)

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/22/2014 09:59 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Wednesday August 19, 1931

This morning at 7:55 we started for the snake dance at Mishongnovi from Holbrook.

1 Small C.c. confluentus DOR 3 mi. N. of Holbrook. Brown not red. Plain grass prairie here, no rocks. Got one whiptail.

Got a small conflue crossing the road 6 mi. N. of Holbrook. Plain dry grass prairie here abouts. Prairie dogs.

Stopped to hunt on a prairie and sandy knoll at 10 mi. N. of Holbrook and got Holbrookias and Whiptails but not as common as yesterday near Canyon Padre.

We got a second fire pinkish rattler crossing the road 22 miles north of Holbrook. We hunted at 25 mi. N. but found lizards scarce. Got a Holbrookia.

Beginning a little before Indian Wells the country becomes increasingly rough and rolling; also drier particularly at higher altitudes.

We hunted on the mesa 22 miles north of Indian Wells for a short time but saw no lizards. In fact we saw none crossing the road in this area

(Continued on Aug. 3d)

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/22/2014 10:07 PM

Thursday August 20, 1931

This morning at Holbrook we took about an hour to clean up the ined and rearranged the load in the car. We started from the auto camp at 8:45.
1 Crotalus C. Confluentus 6 mi. W. of Winslow DOR. This was not a small red but rather a dark olive. Somewhat longer than the small reds but not a light green or a large as a light green.
1 Hypsiglena DOR 13 mi. W. of Winslow (near Dennison) Sandstone. Also a uta stans here.

At 16 miles west of Winslow a large olive green confluentus DOR. This was definitely larger than any of the little Winslow reds. Sandstone, red rock, light grass and brush here.
We went to Meteor Crater and talked to the boy there. He said that rattlers were moderately common - also collared lizards but we didn't see any. We caught a uta ornata symmetrica in the house.

One conflue (small dark) DOR 4 mi. N.

(Continued Aug 1st).

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/22/2014 10:32 PM

Friday August 21, 1931

Today we started from Prescott at 9 AM. First went around to see Rohner at the Santa Fe but he was not in. Talked for half an hour with his chief clerk Lee Cheesboro.

South of Prescott we come to real mountains; the summit is reached 7 mi. south.

South of the summit the slow is much more arid and is covered with chaparral. Sceloporus Consobrinus is seen but is not common.

We stopped for a while 21 miles south of Prescott on the North side of the Kirkland Valley. Here are grass and light brush. At a small pool we found Scaphiopus Hammondii in all stages from tad poles to little toads. Also we collected here 3 Thamnophis eques. (Two died from the heat on the way in to Phoenix) Little whiptails were quite common here. Holbrookia was seen but not collected. This was 2 mi. N. of Kirkland Junction. We got a Crotaphytus 4 mi. S. of Kirkland Junct.

(Continued July 27th 1931)

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/22/2014 10:47 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Saturday August 22, 1931

Today after a hot night we first went around to see Evans collection. He had a few rattlers, scutes and atrox. Nothing worth commenting on except 8 tigris taken in the mountains south of Phoenix. He had a brood of six scutes born the night before, 4 quite dark, 2 lighter. He gave me one of the lighter which was dead. We left the State Capitol for home at noon. West of Phoenix there is alternately desert and cultivation.

1 L. g. boylii M DOR 4 mi. E. of Hassayampa
Clean narrow white stripes. Cultivated fields.

We reached Gila Bend at 2:05 Very hot; not a lizard to be seen anywhere, although we passed many ideal places both rooks and sand. Too hot ardently. If any snakes were out last night they are gone off the road.

Stopped at Sentinel at 3:20 got dips, whip and saw cally but did not collect. Too hot for lizards to be out.

At Reptile Inn near Mohawk with OD Herron saw an atrox with young (6) born today. Says they are usually born in August. He had no rattlers except atrox and cerastes (Continued Aug. 23d)

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/22/2014 10:56 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Sunday August 23, 1931

Spent the day catching up with all kinds of work - basement, zoo and office.
The Xantusia looks OK. Nearest to virgilis but quite different in form.

(Aug 22 Continued)

He tells me that the atrox and scutes are found along the river bottom. His atrox are of all different colors. Some are very dark brown like scutes; others are very light. He had caught an atrox several feet up in a mesquite tree. He handles them all easily but carefully and kindly. He catches most of his cerastes early in the morning by following the tracks. He had had a black tail from the Copper Mts, Betty Lee Mine. Mitch's are always in the rocky country. We left the Reptile Inn at 5:20.

We reached El Centro at 7:00 P.M. Still very hot - nothing seen, evidently too hot for snakes.

We reached home at 10:45. Nothing was seen (Continued Aug 24th)

Saturday September 5, 1931

Worked from 9 AM to 3PM checking rattlers at MVZ. Noted today a ring-neck from Berry Creek, Butte Co, Cal Sept 1/31 which is deep crimson, (not yellow or vermilion) below from head to tail.
A few scattered black dots. Same color ring. Head and body almost black. Very different in every way from similis.

A few records of interest.

Anniella pulchra Contra Costa Co
Coleonyx Variegatus W.C. Hanna

Phyllorhynchus decurtatus San Ignacio 600 ft
Lampropeltis Conjuncta? Comondu
Very thin stripes not over 2 scales wide on dark brown.

Saturday October 31, 1931

This afternoon amongst other misc. work I checked over the American Naturalist up to and including Vol. 21. for rattle references.

Put my nose in the center cage with 394 rattlers today to check that famous odor. Even in this closed space it was barely noticeable and what there was was probably fresh excreta.

Feted odor of Confluentus in breeding season. Brons. arm. Nat. 16:566 (1882)
M Le Conte. Proc. Phita. Acad.
1853 Vol. 6, p. 419 he avers odor very strong, while Beauvois denies it.

Tuesday November 3, 1931

Crotalus ruber 2 mi. N. of San Ysidro
C. atrox Sauceda Mts. 20 mi. S. of Gila Bend
C. cerastes, Mohawk.
C. tigris, Tucson Range, 6 mi. W. of Tucson.
C. Oreganuz? (black rattler) 6 mi. S.E. of Oracle, Oak Zone.
C. lepidus, Franklin Mts., near El Paso
C. lepidus Mt. Livermore, alt. abt.
C. molossus 8400 ft. Davis Mts., Tex

Saturday November 7, 1931

Went to Los Angeles today to the Stanford - USC game. Started at 6:40. A cold drizzly morning. Nothing seen.

Returned starting from Long Beach at about 7:35. South of Laguna a good many toads were seen dead and hopping on the road, but the only one picked up (we had no flash light) was a hyla regilla at San Onofre.

Wednesday November 11, 1931

59 450-650 mm

33 750-850 mm
7 850-1050 mm

16 1

Series B are now all in central cage at zoo. Series A are all in the basement - some killed today.
The juveniles to the number of 124 are now all pickled.

Worked all afternoon on the Snake Dance paper. Think it is now finished except for a few odds and ends and references. Made the selections and arrangements for Appendix 1 today.

Wednesday December 16, 1931

At Yucca the country is rolling rough desert like south of Needles. Hard, not sandy; small rocks. Kingman: Hilly rought and rocky. Chuckawalla country. Lourse: A plain with light brush. After crossing a very long plain at Hackberry it is hilly (almost mountainous) rough and rocky. Cropier: Rough and rocky; Truxton: Another plain surrounded by rolling hills and mountains. Peach Springs: Rolling hills; scattered junipers. Seligman: A plain surrounded by rolling hills. Pineveta is a great plain. Ash Fork: A rolling plain; looks like good rattler country.

Worked all day and evening reading second galley proof of Snake Dance paper.

Tuesday December 22, 1931

From 1/2 way between Albuquerque and Las Vegas southward it is upland rolling prairie. Hills in the foreground; mountains in the background patches of snow. Farms in the valley. This is one hour out of Albug. There are trees in the river washes; scattered light brush on the prairie. Plenty rocks on the hillsides and bluffs. Pueblo villages. At Bernalillo the valley is quite wide and flat.

South of Albuquerque the valley is broad and level; cold with frost. At Isleta still a dry valley; light brush and grass on the hills at the right.

After leaving the valley we reached a rolling prairie with a few scattered rock outcrops. The brush is quite low_mostly bunch grass. Sandia: Upland rolling prairie; bunch grass. Dalies: Rolling prairie; sparse vegetation; scattered sage brush; evidently quite sandy; this particularly evident in railroad cut. Ice in pools. Rio Puerco: Hard red soil; bunch grass and low brush; hilly; mts. near by. North Garcia: Rough and rocky hills; alkali flats; sandstone. Some ground red, some not. South Garcia: Very red. High prairie; hills in the distance. Sparse vegetation.

Notes:

Szlyna

May want to check the spelling on Isleta, or Isbta...hard to make out.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/25/2014 10:37 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Wednesday December 23, 1931

Returned from Chicago at noon today.
This afternoon Paxton C. Hayes came to see me about his proposed snake reserve. Told him definitely that I did not want my name used in connection therewith.

Marmon: High rocky prairie; some red; some yellow sandstone. Quite barren, bunch grass; mts. and buttes in the distance. Didn't see Suivanee but hadn't seen anything particularly different for some time. Not sandy like Dalies. Now come to some fine red sandstone bluffs. Also black sandstone. Now we come to junipers, scattered. This is Quirk. There is plenty of rocky country here, mixed with flats. Mostly black and yellow sandstone here; no red; junipers in the hills. New Laguna: Rocky hills with junipers to the north; a brushy, some-what sandy valley to the south; not red; brush moderately high; patches of snow. This valley is quite large. The soil seems loose, not sandy as at Dalies. Cubero: same. Acomita: Valley has narrowed. Rocky bluffs of yellow sandstone on each side [Cont. next page]

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/25/2014 10:46 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Thursday December 24, 1931

McCartys: Valley has again widened. Some junipers; light brush; rocky bluffs in the distance; snow patches, soil not red. Grants: Just of here there is a verylarge grassy valley; much snow; can't tell if if its sandy or not. There is much black rock toward the west. Surrounded by hills open to the south as far as can be seen. Junipers in the the hills. Grants is quite a town; kids skating on ice. Then we go again along a narrow valley; soil getting redder. Toltec: Another large valley, snow covered now. Blue water: Another great valley, rolling, with rock outcrops. Baca still a great valley with red sandstone bluffs in the distance. This whole country is high valleys, bluffs and mountains; junipers and bunch grass. Rock outcrops. Thoreaw: Still the same kind of country; plenty of snow on the ground; yellowish-red soil; rockey hills in the distance, red as usual. We then cross a pass; the junipers are large like Winona. Perla somewhat lower; no junipers; a rolling snow covered valley, surrounded by red bluffs. Wingate: A somewhat smaller valley surrounded by red bluffs. McCunie:Fort Wingate hedges to be seen to the south.

Notes:

Szlyna

Unsure of the very last sentence, hard to read because part of the word looks like it's cut off and I'm not sure if he is writing hedges.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/25/2014 10:52 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Friday December 25, 1931

Zuni: Very high red bluffs to the north; red soil; sparse vegetation. Gallup: Rocky bare yellow sandstone. The country just east of Gallup is small sagebrush valleys surrounded by yellow sandstone hills. Manuelito: A narrow valley between yellow sandstone bluffs; a pine or two; plenty of snow. At Ariz-N.M. State Line, smae; a narrow valley, sandstone cliffs; deep snow; junipers. Lupton: ditto. Beyond Lupton the ground gets red. Ditto all in town. Houck: Valley a little lider, otherwise the same. The soil is reddish. Querino: Narrow valley; red soil; sandstone on hills; plenty of junipers. A wider valley at Cheto otherwise the same; at Chambers there is quite a prairie off to the north. Soil probably red. At Navaho the hills are gentle in the distance. The country is a slightly rolling prairie. Little Colo. River to the south. Snow lighter; low brush; red brown soil. Pinta: A wide river valley with rocky banks. Red outcrops. Bibo: A sage brush prairie with yellow sand stone outcrops. Adamana: Grass prairie; some low brush. Red brown soil, little snow. Carrizo: River bottom; rocky outcrops and prairie. Arntz: Same.

Notes:

Szlyna

I had no idea what he was trying to write at " Beyond Lupton the ground gets red. Ditto all in town. Houck: Valley a little lider, otherwise the same." It was hard to read.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/25/2014 11:00 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Saturday December 26, 1931

Brush prairie; red soil. Joseph City: Same higher brush; Manila: Same prairie. Havre: Red soil; bunch grass prairie; Hobson: Same. Winslow: Red soil; rather barren prairie; no snow. Dennison: Soil quite red; a little snow: Sunshine: the red outcrops cease and yellow small scattered sandstone begins. The ground is browner; there is little snow. Canyon Diablo: The soil is dark brown and there is much broken sandstone on the ground. The prairie is grassy with small bushes. Hubbard. Grass and small brush prairie. Yellow rockes; dark grey soil. Angell: Large junipers here; plenty snow; sandstone scattered on the ground.

Pineveta is in the midst of a great plain. Only a few small junipers showing through the snow. Gleed is a rough country; snow covered. A great hillside with scattered small trees and a great plain below. Saw the sign this time after missing it last two trips.

Worked all afternoon on annual tabulations. Made good progress.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/25/2014 11:06 AM
  • Szlyna 04/25/2014 11:06 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Sunday December 27, 1931

This morning I made the first draft of the Anniella paper for copeia. Had to work at the office in the afternoon a/c pending rate hearing.

The present is not a good time to undertake highly involved papers because of the rate case. Can only work odd hours and it is difficult to drop and pick up complicated problems.

At present the status of unpublished papers is as follows:
Hoover Dam: In Copeia's hands over 6 months
Snake Dance: Second galley proof returned with corrections to printer yesterday.
Anniella: First draft finished today.
Rattle: Outline complete. Bibliography largely complete. Measurements available but not coordinated. Biblio-references listed by subject.
Santa Fe Rattlers: Statistics compiled.
Locality Bibliography: Introduction and outline prepared. Scope discussed with Schmidt.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/25/2014 11:11 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:27 PM

Dec. Monday 28, 1931

The status of work other than papers as of this date is as follows:

Annual reports to Zoo and NH are ready to write, the statistical data having been compiled. This includes the San Diego County Snake table which is the hardest to work up.

The card files are complete to the midyear. Philip will enter the trip and collection catalogues on the cards next week. After this the San Diego County maps (except snakes which are complete) and the Imperial County maps are to be completed.

Downstairs Cook has nearly all the rattlers complete, except for about one dozen. This statement however does not apply to the latest 394 rattlers from Platteville. On these the measurements and rattles are complete. It is doubtful if the other scale counts will be made, at least for the present.

Recd today a very encouraging letter from Prof. E.T. Bell re originality of my triangle of primes

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
